{
  "id": "ch4",
  "course": "Katzung Pharmacology",
  "chapter": 4,
  "title": "Drug Biotransformation",
  "subtitle": "High-Yield Summary",
  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "1-core-concept",
      "number": 1,
      "title": "Core Concept",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Drug biotransformation = chemical modification of drugs/xenobiotics by the body."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Main purpose",
          "items": [
            "Convert lipophilic drugs into more polar, water-soluble compounds.",
            "Facilitate renal or biliary excretion.",
            "Terminate or modify drug activity."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important",
          "items": [
            "Metabolism usually inactivates drugs.",
            "Some metabolites are active or toxic.",
            "Some drugs are prodrugs and require metabolism for activation."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/01-fig-4-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-1 — Phase I, phase II & direct elimination"
    },
    {
      "id": "2-why-biotransformation-is-needed",
      "number": 2,
      "title": "Why Biotransformation Is Needed",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Many drugs are",
          "items": [
            "Lipophilic",
            "Poorly ionized at physiologic pH",
            "Protein-bound",
            "Easily reabsorbed from renal tubules"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Without metabolism, many drugs would have prolonged action."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Thiopental",
            "Pentobarbital"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/01-fig-4-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-1 — Why biotransformation is needed"
    },
    {
      "id": "3-phase-i-and-phase-ii-reactions",
      "number": 3,
      "title": "Phase I and Phase II Reactions",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Phase I reactions",
          "items": [
            "Introduce or expose functional groups.",
            "Common groups: -OH, -NH2, -SH",
            "Often make drug more polar.",
            "May activate, inactivate, or create toxic metabolites."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Common Phase I reactions",
          "items": [
            "Oxidation",
            "Reduction",
            "Hydrolysis"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Phase II reactions",
          "items": [
            "Conjugation reactions.",
            "Add endogenous molecules to drug or Phase I metabolite.",
            "Usually produce highly polar, inactive metabolites."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Common conjugates",
          "items": [
            "Glucuronic acid",
            "Sulfate",
            "Acetate",
            "Glutathione",
            "Glycine",
            "Methyl groups"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important",
          "items": [
            "Phase II can occur before Phase I.",
            "Example: isoniazid acetylation before hydrolysis."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/02-table-4-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 4-1 — Phase I reactions",
      "imageSupplement": "data_4/03-table-4-1.png",
      "imageSupplementCaption": "TABLE 4-1 — Phase I reactions (continued)"
    },
    {
      "id": "4-main-sites-of-drug-metabolism",
      "number": 4,
      "title": "Main Sites of Drug Metabolism",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Principal organ",
          "items": [
            "Liver"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Other sites",
          "items": [
            "Intestine",
            "Lung",
            "Kidney",
            "Skin",
            "Brain",
            "Plasma",
            "Gut microbiota"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important concept",
          "items": [
            "Oral drugs may undergo first-pass metabolism in intestine and liver."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/01-fig-4-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-1 — Sites of drug metabolism"
    },
    {
      "id": "5-first-pass-metabolism",
      "number": 5,
      "title": "First-Pass Metabolism",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "First-pass effect = metabolism before drug reaches systemic circulation."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Occurs mainly in",
          "items": [
            "Intestinal wall",
            "Liver"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Consequences",
          "items": [
            "Reduced oral bioavailability",
            "Need for higher oral dose or alternative route"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Examples",
          "items": [
            "Morphine",
            "Lidocaine",
            "Midazolam",
            "Cyclosporine",
            "Chlorpromazine"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/15-table-4-7.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 4-7 — Rapidly metabolized drugs (first-pass)"
    },
    {
      "id": "6-microsomal-mixed-function-oxidase-system",
      "number": 6,
      "title": "Microsomal Mixed Function Oxidase System",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Located mainly in smooth endoplasmic reticulum."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Major components",
          "items": [
            "Cytochrome P450 enzymes",
            "NADPH-cytochrome P450 reductase",
            "NADPH",
            "Molecular oxygen"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "General reaction",
          "items": [
            "One oxygen atom enters drug.",
            "One oxygen atom becomes water."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/07-fig-4-3.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-3 — Cytochrome P450 catalytic cycle"
    },
    {
      "id": "7-cytochrome-p450-system",
      "number": 7,
      "title": "Cytochrome P450 System",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Cytochrome P450 enzymes are major Phase I enzymes."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important human CYP enzymes",
          "items": [
            "CYP1A2",
            "CYP2A6",
            "CYP2B6",
            "CYP2C8",
            "CYP2C9",
            "CYP2C19",
            "CYP2D6",
            "CYP2E1",
            "CYP3A4",
            "CYP3A5"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Most important",
          "items": [
            "CYP3A enzymes, especially CYP3A4, metabolize a large share of clinically used drugs."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/05-table-4-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 4-2 — Human liver P450s: substrates & interactions",
      "imageSupplement": "data_4/06-table-4-2.png",
      "imageSupplementCaption": "TABLE 4-2 — CYP3A4 substrates, inducers & inhibitors"
    },
    {
      "id": "8-cyp-induction",
      "number": 8,
      "title": "CYP Induction",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Enzyme induction = increased enzyme expression or reduced degradation."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Effect",
          "items": [
            "Increased metabolism",
            "Reduced drug concentration",
            "Reduced therapeutic effect",
            "Increased toxic metabolite formation for some drugs"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Common inducers",
          "items": [
            "Rifampin",
            "Phenobarbital",
            "Carbamazepine",
            "Phenytoin",
            "St. John’s wort",
            "Smoking",
            "Charcoal-broiled foods",
            "Cruciferous vegetables",
            "Chronic alcohol use"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Clinical examples",
          "items": [
            "Rifampin reduces oral contraceptive effectiveness.",
            "Smoking increases metabolism of some drugs.",
            "St. John’s wort reduces levels of many CYP3A4 substrates."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/09-fig-4-4.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-4 — Relative contributions of CYP pathways"
    },
    {
      "id": "9-cyp-inhibition",
      "number": 9,
      "title": "CYP Inhibition",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Enzyme inhibition = decreased metabolism."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Effect",
          "items": [
            "Increased drug concentration",
            "Increased toxicity risk",
            "Especially important for narrow therapeutic index drugs"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Common inhibitors",
          "items": [
            "Cimetidine",
            "Ketoconazole",
            "Itraconazole",
            "Erythromycin",
            "Clarithromycin",
            "Ritonavir",
            "Grapefruit juice",
            "Fluoxetine",
            "Fluconazole",
            "Amiodarone"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Clinical examples",
          "items": [
            "Grapefruit juice inhibits intestinal CYP3A4.",
            "Macrolides can increase levels of CYP3A4 substrates.",
            "Allopurinol inhibits xanthine oxidase and increases mercaptopurine toxicity."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/09-fig-4-4.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-4 — Relative contributions of CYP and phase II pathways"
    },
    {
      "id": "10-phase-ii-enzymes",
      "number": 10,
      "title": "Phase II Enzymes",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Major Phase II pathways",
          "items": [
            "Enzyme: UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT)",
            "Important for bilirubin, morphine, acetaminophen, lorazepam, and oxazepam"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "B. Sulfation",
          "items": [
            "Enzyme: sulfotransferase",
            "Important for phenols, alcohols, aromatic amines"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "C. Acetylation",
          "items": [
            "Enzyme: N-acetyltransferase (NAT)",
            "Important for isoniazid, sulfonamides, hydralazine"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "D. Glutathione conjugation",
          "items": [
            "Enzyme: glutathione-S-transferase",
            "Important for detoxifying reactive metabolites"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "E. Methylation",
          "items": [
            "Uses S-adenosylmethionine",
            "Important for catecholamines and thiopurines"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/08-table-4-3.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 4-3 — Phase II conjugation reactions"
    },
    {
      "id": "11-toxic-metabolites",
      "number": 11,
      "title": "Toxic Metabolites",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Drug metabolism can produce toxic reactive intermediates."
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Toxicity risk increases when",
          "items": [
            "Normal conjugation pathways are saturated.",
            "Glutathione is depleted.",
            "CYP activation increases.",
            "Liver disease is present."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Important example",
          "items": [
            "Acetaminophen overdose"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/04-fig-4-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-2 — Isoniazid hepatotoxic metabolite"
    },
    {
      "id": "12-acetaminophen-metabolism",
      "number": 12,
      "title": "Acetaminophen Metabolism",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "At therapeutic doses",
          "items": [
            "Mostly glucuronidation and sulfation",
            "Small amount converted by CYP enzymes to toxic NAPQI",
            "NAPQI detoxified by glutathione"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "In overdose",
          "items": [
            "Glucuronidation and sulfation become saturated.",
            "More drug goes through CYP pathway.",
            "NAPQI increases.",
            "Glutathione becomes depleted.",
            "Hepatic injury occurs."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Antidote",
          "items": [
            "N-acetylcysteine"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "group",
          "label": "Mechanism of antidote",
          "items": [
            "Replenishes glutathione",
            "Detoxifies NAPQI"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_4/12-fig-4-5.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 4-5 — Acetaminophen metabolism & toxicity"
    },
    {
